{"id":"1904.03072","submitter":"Atanas Stefanov G.","authors":"Fazel Hadadifard and Atanas G. Stefanov","title":"Sharp relaxation rates for plane waves of reaction-diffusion systems","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1063/5.0004762","report-no":null,"categories":"math.AP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  It is well-known and classical result that spectrally stable traveling waves\nof a general reaction-diffusion system in one spatial dimension are\nasymptotically stable with exponential relaxation rates. In a series of works\nin the 1990's, the authors have considered plane traveling waves for such\nsystems and they have succeeded in showing asymptotic stability for such\nobjects. Interestingly, the (estimates for the) relaxation rates that they have\nexhibited, are all algebraic and dimension dependent. It was heuristically\nargued that as the spectral gap closes in dimensions $n\\geq 2$, algebraic rates\nare the best possible. In this paper, we revisit this issue. We rigorously\ncalculate the sharp relaxation rates in $L^\\infty$ based spaces, both for the\nasymptotic phase and the radiation terms. These turn out to be are indeed\nalgebraic, but about twice better than the best ones obtained in these early\nworks, although this can be mostly attributed to the inefficiencies of using\nSobolev embeddings to control $L^\\infty$ norms by high order $L^2$ based\nSobolev space norms. Finally, we explicitly construct the leading order\nprofiles, both for the phase and the radiation terms. Our approach relies on\nthe method of scaling variables, which provides sharp relaxation rates in a\nclass of weighted $L^2$ spaces as well.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 5 Apr 2019 14:01:54 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-04-22"}
